ode></CSet><CSet fid="ns"><Code value="gtour"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Travel</CodeD><CodeI org="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="628276"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018584-20180325-144929"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Political/General News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gtour"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="glife"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Living/Lifestyle</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gtour"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Top of the News</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Tackling unruly air travellers set to become easier soon</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>UN aviation arm working to expand powers of local police and courts</Para><Para>On a recent Scoot flight to Amritsar in India, a fist fight broke out between two passengers.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Both men were handed over to the local authorities when the plane landed, the airline said.</Para><Para>They would have got off scot-free, though, because under global aviation laws, Indian authorities have no legal powers to pursue the matter. They can act only if the troublemakers had arrived on an Indian carrier.</Para><Para>The rules that apply to all authorities, including in Singapore, could change next year.</Para><Para>A proposal by the International Civil Aviation Organisation (ICAO) - the United Nations' civil aviation arm - to expand the powers of local police and courts in such cases, has already been ratified by 12 member states. Twenty-two signatures are needed for the Montreal Protocol, which will replace the Tokyo Convention, to come into force, ICAO told The Straits Times.</Para><Para>Singapore, which supports the initiative, is in the process of putting in place the necessary legislation to ratify the protocol.</Para><Para>The International Air Transport Association (Iata) that represents global carriers is working with airlines and governments to speed up the global process.</Para><Para>Iata's assistant director for external affairs Tim Colehan said: "Based on our discussions with states, we know that many are in the final stages of ratification so we are optimistic the 2019 target can be met."</Para><Para>He pointed out that in 2016, there were 9,837 reported incidents of unruly behaviour, or one incident per 1,434 flights.</Para><Para>While this was a slight dip from the number in 2015 - one incident per 1,205 flights - there has been an increase in the number of serious incidents that required cabin crew to use restraints; from 113 in 2015 to 169 in 2016.</Para><Para>Mr Colehan warned: "This is a significant problem that affects all geographies and airlines."</Para><Para>Trouble on flights usually occurs when passengers misbehave due to alcohol and drug intoxication, or when they refuse to comply with non-smoking and other regulations, he said. Passengers also get into disputes for other reasons, for example, when someone pushes a seat back during a meal, irritating the passenger behind.</Para><Para>Mr Colehan stressed that all passengers should consume alcohol responsibly and be considerate towards others on flights.</Para><Para>Airport restaurants and bars, and duty free providers also play an important role in ensuring the responsible sales, marketing and promotion of alcohol, he said.</Para><Para>Still, if things get ugly during a flight, passengers should alert cabin crew and not deal with the situation themselves, he advised.</Para><Para>Singapore Airlines (SIA) spokesman Nicholas Ionides said cabin crew are trained to recognise and deal with unruly passengers.</Para><Para>He said: "Some of these methods include politely declining drinks if the crew discerns that the passenger has had too much to drink, and steering passengers towards alternative beverage options.</Para><Para>"In extreme cases where passengers turn physically violent, our crew are also trained in appropriate ways to handle them, which include certain self-defence tactics."</Para><Para>Cathay Pacific has a "zero-tolerance policy" on unruly behaviour, a spokesman stressed. Actions against culprits may include verbal and written warnings, and getting the person to leave the aircraft if it is still on the ground.</Para><Para>Most airlines also have a passenger blacklist, though none will give details.</Para><Para>Mr Ionides said that in cases of inappropriate or unruly behaviour on SIA flights, "a high-level internal committee carries out a review before a course of action is decided upon. Options include warnings, and in extreme cases a temporary or permanent ban on travelling on our flights".</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Karamjit Kaur </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">File photo showing aeroplanes of various airlines at Changi Airport Terminal 2 on Dec 18, 2017. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

